European Commission Charges Apple
---------------------------------

From the Financial Times ( https://www.ft.com/content/898338c2-b9fd-4494-be=
3f-75b7c669c705 ) :

Brussels has accused Apple of stifling competition on its App Store, markin=
g the first time EU regulators have brought charges against a Big Tech grou=
p under new digital rules. The European Commission has been gearing up for =
years to unleash the full authority of its new Digital Markets Act against =
Big Tech. The landmark rules were designed to help start-ups by forcing pow=
erful =E2=80=9Conline gatekeepers=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0most of whom are =
US companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0to open up their businesses to competition. Tec=
h groups had to comply with the law starting from March.

In preliminary findings issued on Monday, regulators in Brussels said they =
were concerned about restrictions Apple is imposing on developers=E2=80=99 =
ability to =E2=80=9Cfreely steer their customers=E2=80=9D by directing them=
 to promotions outside the App Store=E2=80=A6If found guilty, the iPhone ma=
ker faces a penalty of up to 10 per cent of its global annual revenue, mean=
ing any fine could run into tens of billions of dollars. The fines can rise=
 to 20 per cent in the event the offence is repeated, the EU said. Apple sa=
id it was =E2=80=9Cconfident=E2=80=9D in its compliance.

This isn=E2=80=99t a big surprise, but it is a big deal; the European Commi=
ssion=E2=80=99s press release ( https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner=
/detail/en/ip_24_3433 ) has a list of the preliminary findings, which I wil=
l comment on in turn.

The first set of findings are about Apple=E2=80=99s anti-steering provision=
s:

Apple currently has three sets of business terms governing its relationship=
 with app developers, including the App Store=E2=80=99s steering rules. The=
 Commission preliminarily finds that:

The three sets of business terms are (1) Apple=E2=80=99s existing terms, (2=
) a new set of App Store terms that include lower commissions but a =E2=80=
=9CCore Technology Fee=E2=80=9D of =E2=82=AC0.50 per install per year, and =
(3) terms for apps that are distributed using 3rd-party marketplaces.

* None of these business terms allow developers to freely steer their custo=
mers. For example, developers cannot provide pricing information within the=
 app or communicate in any other way with their customers to promote offers=
 available on alternative distribution channels.

I=E2=80=99m honestly very confused on this point: apps distributed through =
the App Store are subject to Apple=E2=80=99s anti-steering provision, but t=
hat provision has been loosened to allow apps to advertise offers on the we=
b; they are, however, limited to a specific trackable link (and those offer=
s can only go on the page that has said link). What I am even more unclear =
about, though, is the fact that the third set of terms don=E2=80=99t includ=
e any sort of anti-steering provision =E2=80=94 the rules governing apps in=
 3rd-party marketplaces are much more limited and primarily about system se=
curity.

I do, as I have noted on multiple occasions, find Apple=E2=80=99s anti-stee=
ring provisions very noxious, and think eliminating them is one of the comp=
romises the company should have made to avoid getting itself into this posi=
tion. To that end, I=E2=80=99m not surprised the European Commission is goi=
ng in for seconds ( https://stratechery.com/2024/apple-fined-by-european-co=
mmission-apples-spotify-press-release-apple-revokes-epics-developer-account=
-again/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nw=
b3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbm=
xpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwc=
zovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDI0L2FwcGxlLWZpbmVkLWJ5LWV1cm9wZWFuLWNvbW1pc3Np=
b24tYXBwbGVzLXNwb3RpZnktcHJlc3MtcmVsZWFzZS1hcHBsZS1yZXZva2VzLWVwaWNzLWRldmV=
sb3Blci1hY2NvdW50LWFnYWluLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzIxOTAxOTA2LCJpYXQiOjE3MTkzMDk5MD=
YsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZ=
DpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRz=
Iiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.gNoj_vuL2N=
jWnzb30rN4SXY9ZmxqVh7GXLNbhbOUdL2CYwA0MAukBx8eIll1clcl3pt4JNWevyaqCVazn5eAt=
EJDKgwv6gI2De6oubPKim83p3wHeHOIGINeQE1QAECCIzvksmgb763fDsBXlZUr48Nso-xqDpBE=
EhNYWbkWcl8OqaEWvTe5DVtPPhWIl3GMmYexIjyln9PIPsJfz6u1nfuI4pPLccsEayG2cvlLIZ6=
uqGxcn5d3ykaWQEYNmZXY09xrxCB1uSdc7Zv2Meu8Ujxc4MCGDRx6aQCrcg2lMqiHug-uLMx9gU=
m3H_EgP6VRMS7_-AqWNg0Q5w-g5DxIBA ) on this issue, but as far as I can tell,=
 the press release is wrong, in that the third set of business terms do not=
 in fact prohibit apps from steering their customers.

* Under most of the business terms available to app developers, Apple allow=
s steering only through =E2=80=9Clink-outs=E2=80=9D, i.e., app developers c=
an include a link in their app that redirects the customer to a web page wh=
ere the customer can conclude a contract. The link-out process is subject t=
o several restrictions imposed by Apple that prevent app developers from co=
mmunicating, promoting offers and concluding contracts through the distribu=
tion channel of their choice.

This one is correct: two out of three is =E2=80=9Cmost=E2=80=9D.

* Whilst Apple can receive a fee for facilitating via the AppStore [sic] th=
e initial acquisition of a new customer by developers, the fees charged by =
Apple go beyond what is strictly necessary for such remuneration. For examp=
le, Apple charges developers a fee for every purchase of digital goods or s=
ervices a user makes within seven days after a link-out from the app.

This is the big one=E2=80=A6maybe. I think this is about the Core Technolog=
y Fee, but the example is about the fee Apple charges for purchases made vi=
a those sanctioned links. Regardless, what is fairly chilling is the line =
=E2=80=9Cthe fees charged by Apple go beyond what is strictly necessary=E2=
=80=9D; that=E2=80=99s a pretty blatant assertion that the European Commiss=
ion considers pricing its prerogative.

If the Commission=E2=80=99s preliminary views were to be ultimately confirm=
ed, none of Apple=E2=80=99s three sets of business terms would comply with =
Article 5(4) of the DMA, which requires gatekeepers to allow app developers=
 to steer consumers to offers outside the gatekeepers=E2=80=99 app stores, =
free of charge. The Commission would then adopt a non-compliance decision w=
ithin 12 months from the opening of proceedings on 25 March 2024.

The conclusion to this section perhaps squares the circle, specifically the=
 phrase =E2=80=9Cfree of charge=E2=80=9D; this must be about the Core Techn=
ology Fee. In short, the European Commission appears to believe that Apple =
charging a Core Technology Fee is ipso facto a violation of anti-steering p=
rovisions. This doesn=E2=80=99t make a lot of sense to me =E2=80=94 the Cor=
e Technology Fee for apps in 3rd-party app stores doesn=E2=80=99t have anyt=
hing to do with steering provisions =E2=80=94 but there is a certain bit of=
 logic here: specifically, Apple claims that the Core Technology Fee is com=
pensation for access to Apple=E2=80=99s IP; my takeaway is that the Europea=
n Commission doesn=E2=80=99t want to come out and straight up say that Appl=
e can=E2=80=99t charge for access to its IP, so is instead couching its cha=
rge under the anti-steering provision.

The European Commission is also opening a new investigation into Apple abou=
t its treatment of 3rd-party app stores, including the levying of said Core=
 Technology Fee, the fact it takes multiple steps to install 3rd-party app =
stores, and the eligibility requirements for developers seeking to offer 3r=
d-party app stores. The first item in particular gets at the IP-monetizatio=
n question specifically: can Apple charge for access to its IP, or does the=
 DMA compel it to offer access for free? I wish that Apple offered access f=
or free, at least via 3rd-party app stores (which absolutely should have a =
multi-step installation process that makes clear to users the risks), but I=
 have a hard time on principle compelling them to do so; the convoluted nat=
ure of this press release makes me think the European Commission does as we=
ll.

Apple Delays New Features for E.U.
----------------------------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-06-21/apple-w=
on-t-roll-out-ai-tech-in-eu-market-over-regulatory-concerns ) :

Apple Inc. is withholding a raft of new technologies from hundreds of milli=
ons of consumers in the European Union, citing concerns posed by the bloc=
=E2=80=99s regulatory attempts to rein in Big Tech. The company announced F=
riday that it would block the release of Apple Intelligence, iPhone Mirrori=
ng and SharePlay Screen Sharing from users in the EU this year, because the=
 Digital Markets Act allegedly forces it to downgrade the security of its p=
roducts and services.

=E2=80=9CWe are concerned that the interoperability requirements of the DMA=
 could force us to compromise the integrity of our products in ways that ri=
sk user privacy and data security,=E2=80=9D Apple said in a statement.

The EU=E2=80=99s DMA forces dominant technology platforms to abide by a lon=
g list of do=E2=80=99s and don=E2=80=99ts. Tech services are prohibited fro=
m favoring their own offerings over those of rivals. They=E2=80=99re barred=
 from combining personal data across their different services; blocked from=
 using information they collect from third-party merchants to compete again=
st them; and have to allow users to download apps from rival platforms. As =
part of the rules, the EU has designated six of the biggest tech companies =
as =E2=80=9Cgatekeepers=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 powerful platforms that require =
stricter scrutiny. In addition to Apple, that list includes Microsoft Corp.=
, Google parent Alphabet Inc. and Facebook owner Meta Platforms Inc.

It=E2=80=99s obviously difficult to separate this decision from the Europea=
n Commission case above, and a lot of angry European Apple users are accusi=
ng the company of being spiteful in withholding these features from the Eur=
opean Union, at least for now. However, I think I agree with the theory put=
 forward by my Dithering ( https://dithering.fm/ ) co-host John Gruber in t=
his morning=E2=80=99s episode: these folks don=E2=80=99t really understand =
just how far-reaching the DMA is.

Specifically, there is a lot of angst about the App Store, and indeed, the =
case above is about Apple=E2=80=99s App Store policies. The DMA, though, is=
 much more far-reaching than that; the excerpt above rightly identifies the=
 interoperability requirements as the more meaningful factor affecting Appl=
e=E2=80=99s decision. Consider iPhone Mirroring: given that the iPhone is a=
 designated gatekeeper platform, is Apple allowed to enable iPhone screen-s=
haring with a Mac but not with Windows or Linux? Or SharePlay Screen Sharin=
g: can Apple allow you to jointly view apps via Facetime, but not other VoI=
P services? Or the big one, Apple Intelligence: can the semantic index be a=
vailable to Siri, but not other voice assistants?

Another angle on this is data sharing; Article 5 states ( https://www.eu-di=
gital-markets-act.com/Digital_Markets_Act_Article_5.html ) :

The gatekeeper shall not=E2=80=A6combine personal data from the relevant co=
re platform service with personal data from any further core platform servi=
ces or from any other services provided by the gatekeeper or with personal =
data from third-party services.

This pretty expressly forbids Apple Intelligence=E2=80=99s core differentia=
tion: the entire reason why Apple Intelligence is compelling is that Apple,=
 by virtue of controlling the platform, has access to data that no one else=
 does. The promise of Apple Intelligence is that Apple can leverage that ac=
cess to provide AI functionality that no one else can. However, Apple Intel=
ligence is a =E2=80=9Cfurther core platform service=E2=80=9D and the DMA fo=
rbids it from accessing personal data from the core platform service!

More broadly, what we see from the E.U. again and again is outright hostili=
ty to integration; everything must be modular, immediately. The problem wit=
h this insistence, though, is that integration is essential to inventing ne=
w experiences. To go back to Professor Clayton Christensen and The Innovato=
r=E2=80=99s Solution ( https://claytonchristensen.com/books/the-innovators-=
solution/ ) :

When there is a performance gap =E2=80=94 when product functionality and re=
liability are not yet good enough to address the needs of customers in a gi=
ven tier of the market =E2=80=94 companies must compete by making the best =
possible products. In the race to do this, firms that build their products =
around proprietary, interdependent architectures enjoy an important competi=
tive advantage against competitors whose product architectures are modular,=
 because the standardization inherent in modularity takes too many degrees =
of design freedom away from engineers, and they cannot optimize performance=
.

To close the performance gap with each new product generation, competitive =
forces compel engineers to fit the pieces of their systems together in ever=
-more-efficient ways in order to wring the most performance possible out of=
 the technology that is available. When firms must compete by making the be=
st possible products, they cannot simply assemble standardized components, =
because from an engineering point of view, standardization of interfaces (m=
eaning fewer degrees of design freedom) would force them to hack away from =
the frontier of what is technologically possible. When the product is not g=
ood enough, backing off from the best that can be done means that you=E2=80=
=99ll fall behind. Companies that compete with proprietary, interdependent =
architectures must be integrated.

The E.U. has basically made this illegal for the biggest tech companies: yo=
u can=E2=80=99t deliver an integrated experience, even if the technology is=
n=E2=80=99t yet good enough to be modularized. This is obviously bad in gen=
eral, but it=E2=80=99s particularly bad for Apple, which is entirely predic=
ated on integration ( https://stratechery.com/2013/clayton-christensen-got-=
wrong/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb=
3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmx=
pbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwcz=
ovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDEzL2NsYXl0b24tY2hyaXN0ZW5zZW4tZ290LXdyb25nLyJdf=
SwiZXhwIjoxNzIxOTAxOTA2LCJpYXQiOjE3MTkzMDk5MDYsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBh=
